subSubSection.paragraph:
Subspecies. The Korean populations are considered to belong to subsp. seoki independently from the nominal subspecies in Japan and subsp. chinensis in eastern China (
Fig. 11
).

Adult. Active from early May to as late as late September, depending on brood (three broods in C. Korea ). Males often puddle (
Fig. 12
), and they feed on carrion or fermenting fluxes on trees. Males occasionally fly to and pass by mountain peaks or ridges and sometimes are territorial and engage in hilltopping. Females are attracted to fermenting fluids, especially fluxes issuing from oak trees.
